{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"627b4e2d-93ac-49c8-994c-cd803245dbea","content":"The project doesn't exist in this workspace, but here's how to configure it.\n\nCreate (or edit) `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace root:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout (the standard for local MCP servers).\n- **`command` / `args`** — uses `dotnet run` to build and launch your project. Paths are relative to the workspace root.\n- If you publish a standalone binary instead, replace with `\"command\": \"./path/to/MyMcpServer\"`.\n- You can add `\"env\": { \"KEY\": \"value\" }` for environment variables your server needs.\n\nAfter saving, open the **Copilot Chat** panel in agent mode (`@workspace /agent` or Ctrl+Shift+I) — VS Code will automatically discover and start the server.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e34a699b-7124-4010-833f-e7e8d45c339e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The project doesn't exist in the current directory. That's fine — the user is asking how to configure it, not asking me to build anything. I can give them the configuration guidance directly.","outputTokens":341,"requestId":"201B:3D936D:1670C50:191CA17:6A0521C1"},"id":"980f73b8-4062-4859-a75d-0e5d3657b5c5","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:13:46.394Z","parentId":"33a48fbd-a092-4d5e-97ad-412df481f388"}
